{
  "text": " Alright, let's go. Number 10. Turbulence. You've watched it your whole life. Coffee stirring, smoke curling, water rushing over a rock. You've never once thought it was unsolved. But turbulence, one of the most common physical phenomena on Earth, has no working mathematical theory. We can land rovers on Mars. We cannot explain why your coffee swirls the way it does. Physicists call it the last great unsolved problem of classical physics. Is it a pattern? Partially. Is it predictable? No. Does any current model fully describe it? Not even close. Feynman said it was the most important unsolved problem in all of classical physics. That was in 1964. Nothing has changed. We still don't know. Number 9. The measurement problem. Right now, the particle you're made of doesn't have a fixed position, or it exists as a probability cloud smeared across space until something measures it. Then it snaps into reality. That's not metaphor. That's quantum mechanics. But here's what no one can answer. What counts as a measurement? Is it a detector? A camera? A conscious observer? Does the universe require something to be watching in order to exist? Physicists have debated this for 100 years. Copenhagen says, don't ask. Many worlds says, every outcome happens simultaneously. Neither can be tested. The equations work perfectly. The interpretation is completely unsolved. We are using a tool we don't understand to describe a reality we can't define, and somehow that's considered acceptable.",
